%I A395410 #4 Apr 27 2026 00:21:10
%S A395410 1,1,1,3,22,488,27376,2955486,512457676,130095650766
%N A395410 Number of unlabeled minimally 4-rigid graphs on n vertices obtained from 0-extensions.
%C A395410 A graph G is d-rigid, if every generic realization p in dimension d yields a framework (G,p) that is infinitesimally d-rigid; i.e., all its infinitesimal flexes are trivial. It is minimally d-rigid if it is d-rigid but looses this property upon deletion of any edge.
%C A395410 A d-dimensional 0-extension of a graph adds a new vertex and connects it to d other vertices. If the original graph is minimally d-rigid, so is the graph obtained from the 0-extension.
%C A395410 The sequence counts graphs that can be obtained from 4-dimensional 0-extensions starting with the complete graph on 4 vertices.
%C A395410 These are also known as maximal 4-degenerate graphs.
%H A395410 Allan Bickle, <a href="https://doi.org/10.20429/tag.2024.000105">A Survey of Maximal k-degenerate Graphs and k-Trees</a>, Theory and Applications of Graphs 0(1), Article 5, 2024.
%H A395410 Matteo Gallet, Georg Grasegger, Matthias Himmelmann and Jan Legerský, <a href="https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2505.22652">PyRigi -- a general-purpose Python package for the rigidity and flexibility of bar-and-joint frameworks</a>, arXiv:2505.22652 [math.MG], 2025.
%H A395410 Georg Grasegger, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18570095">Dataset of minimally d-rigid graphs obtained from 0-extensions</a>, 2026.
%H A395410 Georg Grasegger, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.7457820">RigiComp - A Mathematica package for computational rigidity of graphs</a>, 2022.
%H A395410 Martin Larsson, <a href="https://github.com/martinkjlarsson/nauty-laman-plugin">Nauty Laman plugin</a>
%H A395410 PyRigi Developers, <a href="https://pyrigi.github.io/PyRigi/math/rigidity.html">Rigidity Theory</a>, 2025.
%H A395410 Walter Whiteley, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1090/conm/197">Some matroids from discrete applied geometry</a>, 1996.
%e A395410 The complete graphs on five vertices is the result of a 4-dimensional 0-etxension on the complete graph on four vertices. A 4-dimensional 0-extension from this graph yields a complete graph on six vertices with one edge removed. There are three graphs that can be obtained from the previous one by adding a new vertex and connecting it to 4 of the existing vertices.
%Y A395410 Cf. A273468, A395194, A394820.
